Review: People in dreams, ought to call them when you wake. "Hello, dreamed of you" , love woke meto cling so desperately to your only chance at happiness and to be so afraid when all that could fade, is conveyed so effortlessly.moments of contemplative silence and hesitation, interspersed with loud, strikingly composed scenes lead to a hypnotic and endearing combination.the fireworks scene is something truly magical, like the closest visual representation of utter euphoria ever put to film,…

Movie: The Tokyo Night Sky Is Always the Densest Shade of Blue
I Don't Want to Sleep Alone

Review: the unmatched energy Yang Kuei-mei brings into this? the contextualisation of musical numbers as coping mechanisms?? the fact that the shitty apartment building still serves as a set piece for the musicals signifying how hard it's become to reject reality ??!idk about u but frankly WE LOVE TO SEE IT!!!!!

Tsai has an uncanny ability to warp interiors, making them seem so unfamiliar despite how much time we spend in them, and to make even the most mundane locations seem otherworldly, such as in my favourite shot in the film where a bathouse becomes a limbo of bodies struggling to find a way out.
THE WAY I FUCKING CHOKED WHEN I REALISED THIS EXISTED OH MY GOD WONG HURRY UP WITH THIS!!!!!!
it took me way too long to finally watch this. here's to longing unfulfilled , here's to love and how painful it is to lose it, and here's to this film for understanding that pain so well.
